      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While alternatives like expanding public transit or enforcing strict low-emission zones exist, they are often insufficient on their own to drastically cut vehicle emissions in a city as massive as New York. Congestion pricing is uniquely effective because it directly targets the root cause of gridlock—excess private vehicle use—making it a non-negotiable tool for rapid decarbonization. Without this specific revenue stream and demand-suppression mechanism, cities will struggle to meet aggressive climate goals without resorting to even more intrusive and costly mandates.",
